I think self-deprecation can frequently be a trap, and it&#039;s one I&#039;ve been prone to for a long time, though I&#039;ve tried to ameliorate the tendency a bit. For me, Hikaru no Go has been helpful in finding better language for confidence: it&#039;s not that I want to go around sure that I will win. Instead, I want to show *fighting spirit* - to assert myself and force my opponent to cut off my head if he wants to kill me (to borrow a phrase from Sai&#039;s second game with Akira). Thinking of games this way has helped me learn how to deal better with losing and to relish the chance to play a game against someone stronger.
I play some of my best go these days against Shifu, because I feel confident that he&#039;ll ultimately destroy me, but I relish the chance to force him to treat me as an opponent who can be dangerous.
I&#039;ve displayed some of my old bad habits in the past with you, pitying myself for getting killed and arguing that you&#039;re better, which is total bull shit. I apologize! Far better to smile broadly and say, &quot;Do your best! I know I will. Let&#039;s fight!&quot;
